import statsmodels.formula.api as smf
import statsmodels.api as sm
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

#10b -> Logistic Regression
weekly["DirCoded"]= [1 if d=='Up' else 0 for d in weekly["Direction"]]
X=weekly.drop(["Direction","Today","Year","DirCoded"],axis=1)
Y=weekly["Direction"]

lr=LogisticRegression()
lr.fit(X,Y)
print("Intercept:\t"+ str(lr.intercept_) + "\nCoefficient:\t" + str(lr.coef_))

Intercept:	[0.26680422]
Coefficient:	[[-0.04123854  0.05840384 -0.01605138 -0.02776243 -0.01446302 -0.02270963]]

model=smf.logit("DirCoded ~ " + "+".join(X.columns),data=weekly)

In [15]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

#10c -> Confusion Matrix
probabilities=result.predict(exog=X)
predictions=["Up" if e>0.5 else "Down" for e in probabilities]
print(pd.DataFrame(confusion_matrix(Y,predictions),['True Down','True Up'], ['Predicted Down','Predicted Up']))

           Predicted Down  Predicted Up
True Down              54           430
True Up                48           557

From the Confusion Matrix we see that the model predicts many of the observations as $Up$. This leads to a very low recall as it also classifies a majority of the $True Down$ observations as $Up$.

#12d -> function to compute x^a
def Power3(x,a):
    prod=1
    for i in range(a):
        prod=prod*x
        
    return prod
